  Name: Guzeppi
  Icon: {fileID: -1465489678553493566, guid: bdf9b2df1b7e9ab48b44781ca0257510, type: 3}
  HasInteraction: 0
  interactionType: 2
  Greeting: Guzeppi the Smugler
  Day1Dialog:
  - I tend the wounded, boy. The first cannonballs have landed; already men are hurt.
    Some have deep cuts, others shattered bones. Even a small untreated wound can
    become fatal. At night, the gravely injured are carried to Fort St. Angelo for
    care. Survival is fragile here.
  Day2FirstTimeDialog:
  - "Cannon fire tears men apart. Broken bones, deep cuts, burns \u2014 we treat
    what we can with bandages, poultices, and splints. Some soldiers must be taken
    at night to Fort St. Angelo, away from the front, to give them a chance at life"
  Day2MetBeforeDialog:
  - You return. Yesterday, wounds; today, infections worsen. Dysentery and fever
    strike the wounded as the infirmary fills. Each life saved feels like a miracle,
    yet many die despite our care.
  Day3FirstTimeDialog:
  - "The enemy is closer. Cannon fire is constant. Every new arrival has fresh wounds:
    cuts, musket shots, splintered bones. Night carries the gravely injured to Fort
    St. Angelo, but some don\u2019t survive the trip."
  Day3MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Yesterday, we treated musket wounds; today, cannon injuries and infections overwhelm
    the infirmary. Each poultice and stitch may save a life, yet many will not survive
    Dragut\u2019s bombardment."
  Day4FirstTimeDialog:
  - "Bandages, herbs, wine \u2014 nearly gone. Wounds fester, infections spread.
    Each life clings by a thread, boy, and every night we risk carrying the gravely
    wounded to Fort St. Angelo under fire."
  Day4MetBeforeDialog:
  - Yesterday, I patched what I could; today, disease and wounds ravage the fort.
    Some of the men we saved last night are gone by morning. St. Elmo holds, but
    at terrible cost.
  Day5FirstTimeDialog:
  - "Tomorrow may see the bloodiest day yet. Many men have already died. Every life
    here is fragile, and the fort\u2019s defenders cling desperately to hope."
  Day5MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Final day, boy. Every patient, every wound, every life depends on what we\u2019ve
    done. Remember the faces here; they are the price of holding St. Elmo against
    overwhelming odds."
  dayNumber: 1
  metOnday1: 0
